{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"95012682-15cf-41b3-b7d6-e7cc3b35559c","content":"CLR activation logs won't help here. They only cover **how the CLR runtime is loaded** (version selection, shim behavior) — not application-level exceptions like `NullReferenceException`.\n\nA `NullReferenceException` means your code is dereferencing a `null` reference at runtime. To diagnose it, you'd want:\n\n1. **The stack trace** from the exception (check console output, event logs, or logs).\n2. **A crash dump** — I can help you set up dump collection if needed (use `dotnet-dump` or environment variables).\n3. **The source code** around the crash site so we can inspect what's null.\n\n**Can you share:**\n- The full exception message and stack trace?\n- Or the relevant source code / project?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7b444ac4-0560-431f-85aa-700123f02b6c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs are about the shim (mscoree.dll) selecting and loading the correct CLR version — they won't help diagnose a NullReferenceException, which is a runtime exception in the application code.\n\n\nI should clarify this to the user since the skill won't actually address their problem.","outputTokens":377,"requestId":"D7C5:246CF2:E5B4D7:108F519:69F2B12F"},"id":"71ac065e-dacf-42f8-bc8d-b901e63cbb44","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:32:42.726Z","parentId":"77f10cac-4470-4ed1-9973-a758e20a2f65"}
